ntral economic control. Both statistical data and case studies (based on interviews and Presidential documents) are brought to bear on four topics. They are: 1) the political manipulation of the economy in election years, 2) the new international electoral-economic cycle, 3) the decisive role of political leaders and parties in shaping macroeconomic outcomes, and 4) the response of the electorate to changing economic conditions. Finally, the book clarifies a central question in political economy: How can national economic policy be conducted in both a democratic and a competent fashion?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomic policy. 0aMacroeconomics. 0aPolitical science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh  aAustralia.  aBelgium.  aCameron, David R.  aCarter, Jimmy.  aCongress.  aDemocratic platform.  aDenmark.  aDowns, Anthony.  aFederalist Papers.  aFiorina, Morris P.  aFord, Gerald R.  aGermany.  aGoodhart, C.A.E.  aHeclo, Hugh.  aHibbs, Douglas, Jr.  aItaly.  aJohnson administration.  aKennedy, John F.  aKirschen, E. S.  aKramer, Gerald H.  aLindbeck, Assar.  aMiller, Warren E.  aNixon, Richard F.  aRose, Richard.  aSchneider, Friedrich.  aStokes, Donald E.  aTobin, James.  aadministrative agencies.  aausterity measures.  abureaucracy.  aeconomic policy-makers.  aelection dates.  aincome equalization.  ainflation.  amacroeconomic policy.  aodd-numbered years.  apolitical ideology.  asocial security.  aveterans benefits.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691219417zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691219417423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.